<quality>
- If you find yourself passing `true`/`false`, favor two separate methods or a small struct.
- Only modify files directly related to the current user story or bugfix; avoid unrelated edits.
- Do not optimize code until it is proven necessary by real performance concerns.
- Follow Go best practices and idioms:
  - Use interfaces for behavior
  - Keep interfaces small and focused
  - Prefer composition over inheritance
  - Use meaningful names that explain purpose
- For any complex input validation, create a dedicated struct with validation methods.
- Use dependency injection via interfaces for better testability.
</quality>

<security>
- Whenever we need to make any changes to the database, make sure to take baby steps. Smallest increments we can.
- Only use force push when absolutely necessary (e.g., after rebasing or amending commits that were already pushed).
When force pushing is required, always use --force-with-lease instead of -f to ensure you don't accidentally overwrite others' work.
Try a regular git push first - only use force options if the regular push fails with a non-fast-forward error.

- Prefer well-maintained, production-tested Go packages with:
  - Active maintenance
  - Good test coverage
  - No known security vulnerabilities
  - Clear documentation

Run gosec and nancy for security scanning after adding new dependencies.
</security>

<testing>
- If a test appears to be flaky, it must be fixed. Look for any race conditions, timing issues, or goroutine leaks.
- When tests fail, only fix them one at a time. Run just the failing test until it succeeds. Then rerun all, and fix the next one. Repeat until all pass.
- Do not use mocks when testing, if at all possible. Favor interfaces and dependency injection to make code more testable. Mocks are a last resort.

Cover both happy and unhappy paths.

Do not assert against specific CSS values or HTML elements. Focus on functionality and content.

Use testify/assert for clearer test assertions.

For HTML5 validation (e.g., required fields), test the attributes directly rather than trying to submit invalid data.

# Testing Required Fields

When testing form fields that are required:

1. Test HTML5 validation by checking the required attribute:
```go
func TestRequiredFields(t *testing.T) {
    doc := parseHTML(t, html)
    email := doc.Find("input[name='email']")
    assert.Equal(t, "true", email.Attr("required"))
    password := doc.Find("input[name='password']")
    assert.Equal(t, "true", password.Attr("required"))
}
```

2. DO NOT test for server-side "blank" validation messages by disabling HTML5 validation. The HTML5 validation prevents these from ever being shown to users.

3. DO test other server-side validations that HTML5 cannot handle:
   - Uniqueness constraints
   - Format/regex validations
   - Complex validations (e.g., password confirmation matching)
   - Custom business logic

Example:
```go
func TestEmailUniqueness(t *testing.T) {
    // Good - Testing server-side uniqueness validation
    existingUser := createTestUser(t, "taken@example.com")
    
    input := SignupInput{
        Email:    "taken@example.com",
        Name:     "Another User",
        Password: "password123",
    }
    
    _, err := authService.Signup(input)
    assert.ErrorIs(t, err, ErrEmailTaken)
}

// Bad - Testing what HTML5 validation already prevents
func TestMissingFields(t *testing.T) {
    // Don't do this - HTML5 prevents this scenario
    input := SignupInput{}
    _, err := authService.Signup(input)
    assert.ErrorIs(t, err, ErrEmailRequired)
}
```

# Testing Guidelines

1. Use table-driven tests for multiple test cases
2. Use meaningful test names that describe the scenario
3. Follow the Arrange-Act-Assert pattern
4. Use subtests for better organization
5. Clean up test data in defer functions

Example:
```go
func TestUserSignup(t *testing.T) {
    tests := []struct {
        name    string
        input   SignupInput
        wantErr error
    }{
        {
            name: "valid input succeeds",
            input: SignupInput{
                Email:    "test@example.com",
                Password: "password123",
                Name:     "Test User",
            },
            wantErr: nil,
        },
        {
            name: "duplicate email fails",
            input: SignupInput{
                Email:    "existing@example.com",
                Password: "password123",
                Name:     "Test User",
            },
            wantErr: ErrEmailTaken,
        },
    }

    for _, tt := range tests {
        t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            // Arrange
            db := setupTestDB(t)
            defer cleanupTestDB(t, db)
            
            if tt.name == "duplicate email fails" {
                createTestUser(t, tt.input.Email)
            }
            
            // Act
            _, err := authService.Signup(tt.input)
            
            // Assert
            assert.ErrorIs(t, err, tt.wantErr)
        })
    }
}
```

# Frontend Testing

1. Use Playwright for end-to-end testing
2. Focus on user journeys and critical paths
3. Test both JavaScript and no-JavaScript scenarios
4. Use data-testid attributes for test selectors
5. Keep selectors in a central location

Example:
```go
func TestLoginFlow(t *testing.T) {
    // Start Playwright
    pw := playwright.Must(playwright.Run())
    defer pw.Stop()
    
    browser := pw.Chromium.Must(pw.Chromium.Launch())
    defer browser.Close()
    
    page := browser.Must(browser.NewPage())
    
    // Navigate to login
    page.Must(page.Goto("http://localhost:8080/login"))
    
    // Fill form
    page.Must(page.Fill("[data-testid=email]", "test@example.com"))
    page.Must(page.Fill("[data-testid=password]", "password123"))
    
    // Submit
    page.Must(page.Click("[data-testid=submit]"))
    
    // Assert redirect
    assert.Equal(t, "/dashboard", page.Must(page.URL()))
}
```

# Accessibility Testing

1. All interactive elements MUST be keyboard accessible
2. Use semantic HTML elements appropriately
3. Include proper ARIA attributes where needed
4. Test with screen readers
5. Maintain proper heading hierarchy

Custom widgets (dropdowns, modals) MUST have proper ARIA attributes (aria-expanded, aria-haspopup, etc.)

Examples:
```html
<!-- Good - Button with clear purpose -->
<button 
    type="button"
    aria-haspopup="true"
    aria-expanded="false"
    aria-controls="user-menu"
    data-testid="user-menu-button">
    Open Menu
</button>

<!-- Bad - Generic click handler -->
<div onclick="toggleMenu()" role="button">
    Menu
</div>
```
